So yesterday you had a presentation from the Department of Health and Human Services, and Deb Sheets spoke about the Choices for Independence program, and I'm going to just review it really quickly.

2133
04:01:34.500 --> 04:01:38.500
So CFI is a waiver service under Medicaid.

2134
04:01:38.500 --> 04:01:42.500
It's really intended for elderly and adult citizens.

2135
04:01:42.500 --> 04:01:50.000
Adults can be anywhere from 21 and up who need nursing home level of care.

2136
04:01:50.000 --> 04:01:54.500
And so those folks go through a financial eligibility.

2137
04:01:54.500 --> 04:02:04.500
So it's based, it's primarily for low income individuals and a clinical eligibility where they're assessed by a department nurse.

2138
04:02:04.500 --> 04:02:10.500
And then they're determined to be eligible for services by BES staff.

2139
04:02:10.500 --> 04:02:22.000
But I think the important thing to remember here is that these people are determined to need a nursing home level of care.

2140
04:02:22.000 --> 04:02:27.500
So they're very vulnerable and they need a lot of support.

2141
04:02:27.500 --> 04:02:37.500
But the beauty of the Choices for Independence program is it allows people to live at home with supportive services.

2142
04:02:37.500 --> 04:02:48.500
And let's face it, most people would prefer to be at home rather than in a group setting or a nursing home.

2143
04:02:48.500 --> 04:02:58.500
But the other beauty of CFI, when it's working well, is that it's a really good investment for the state.

2144
04:02:58.500 --> 04:03:08.500
The average annual cost is less than $20,000 per year per individual compared to over $50,000 for nursing home care.

2145
04:03:08.500 --> 04:03:10.500
So, Mr.

2146
04:03:10.500 --> 04:03:18.000
Chairman, you asked that when we speak, we talk about the lines that we're addressing.

2147
04:03:18.000 --> 04:03:23.500
And yesterday, I believe that Karen Rounds showed you this page.

2148
04:03:23.500 --> 04:03:27.500
