2153
04:03:44.000 --> 04:03:50.000
And you'll notice that this line has about $56 million in it.

2154
04:03:50.000 --> 04:03:53.500
I call this the kitchen sink line.

2155
04:03:53.500 --> 04:03:56.000
There's a lot in this.

2156
04:03:56.000 --> 04:03:58.000
There's personal care services.

2157
04:03:58.000 --> 04:04:00.500
There is meals on wheels.

2158
04:04:00.500 --> 04:04:04.500
The case managers get paid from this line.

2159
04:04:04.500 --> 04:04:12.000
Things like pill planners, equipment that people might need at home is in class 506.

2160
04:04:12.000 --> 04:04:19.000
And then class 529 home health waiver services are some specific home health services.

2161
04:04:19.000 --> 04:04:30.500
So I'm going to, and I'm here today to talk specifically about the home health services that are delivered in these two lines.

2162
04:04:30.500 --> 04:04:32.500
Thank you.

2163
04:04:32.500 --> 04:04:41.000
here today to talk specifically about the home health services that are delivered in these two lines.

2164
04:04:41.000 --> 04:04:45.000
So let's talk about what those services are.

2165
04:04:45.000 --> 04:04:49.000
For CFI clients, they can receive nursing visits.

2166
04:04:49.000 --> 04:05:00.500
Keep in mind that if they were in a nursing home, they would be a nurse overseeing their care 24 hours a day.

2167
04:05:00.500 --> 04:05:06.000
So nurses visit the client as determined based on their needs.

2168
04:05:06.000 --> 04:05:12.000
It might be once a week, twice a week, once a month.

2169
04:05:12.000 --> 04:05:20.000
And there are clinical assessments done to check in to see how the client is doing.

2170
04:05:20.000 --> 04:05:22.500
They put together care plans.

2171
04:05:22.500 --> 04:05:26.000
They address wound care and catheter care.

2172
04:05:26.000 --> 04:05:32.000
A lot of what they do is help people with their medications.

2173
04:05:32.000 --> 04:05:36.000
So it comes from filling the pill planners.

2174
04:05:36.000 --> 04:05:46.000
When the doctor changes the medication, it's a nurse that goes to the home to change out the pill planner.

2175
04:05:46.000 --> 04:05:51.500
And be sure that clients are getting the medications they need.

2176
04:05:51.500 --> 04:05:56.000
There's also a lot of patient and family education.

2177
04:05:56.000 --> 04:05:58.500
This is what nurses do.

2178
04:05:58.500 --> 04:06:01.500
They help people understand their illnesses.

2179
04:06:01.500 --> 04:06:26.000
They help them understand how they can care for themselves, what they need to do, for instance, to deal with their diabetes in terms of eating well, what they need to be careful of if they have congestive heart failure so that they're not eating too much salty food.

2180
04:06:26.000 --> 04:06:29.500
So this is what really nurses do.

2181
04:06:29.500 --> 04:06:33.000
And then they supervise home health aides.

2182
04:06:33.000 --> 04:06:36.000
And this is in class 529.

2183
04:06:36.000 --> 04:06:40.000
The next category is home health aid services.

2184
04:06:40.000 --> 04:06:49.000
And there's a lot of correlation between what home health aides do and what personal care providers do.

2185
04:06:49.000 --> 04:06:53.000
But home health aides are licensed nursing assistants.

2186
04:06:53.000 --> 04:06:56.500
They're licensed by the Board of Nursing.

2187
04:06:56.500 --> 04:07:08.000
They've completed 100 hours of training and they work under the supervision of a nurse and they observe and they report medical conditions.

2188
04:07:08.000 --> 04:07:11.500
They assist with bathing, toileting, dental care.

2189
04:07:11.500 --> 04:07:18.000
They help with the transfers in and out of bed, dressing, walking, feeding.

2190
04:07:18.000 --> 04:07:22.000
They can be delegated to actually administer medications.

2191
04:07:22.000 --> 04:07:27.500
So they're a higher level of service than personal care services.

2192
04:07:27.500 --> 04:07:30.500
These are also in class 529.

2193
04:07:30.500 --> 04:07:34.000
Personal care services is in class 506.

2194
04:07:34.000 --> 04:07:36.500
And these are unlicensed personnel.

2195
04:07:36.500 --> 04:07:45.000
They have about 16 hours of training, six of which is specifically state mandated dementia care training.

2196
04:07:45.000 --> 04:07:55.000
And I might add that the LNAs also have to go through those six hours of mandated dementia care training.

2197
04:07:55.000 --> 04:07:59.500
And personal care providers do bathing, toileting, dental care.

2198
04:07:59.500 --> 04:08:04.500
Once again, they assist with these activities of daily living.

2199
04:08:04.500 --> 04:08:14.000
They remind people to take their medications, and they might do transportation to, say, grocery, pharmacy, and other services.

2200
04:08:14.000 --> 04:08:16.500
So what's the difference here?

2201
04:08:16.500 --> 04:08:47.500
Really, what you're talking about here is you might send an L&A to a CFI client who has some serious medical conditions, whereas somebody here might get personal care services for somebody who may not have medical conditions, but is just simply frail and needs some help, you know, around the house, getting up and out of bed, that sort of thing.

2202
04:08:47.500 --> 04:08:50.000
And some clients get both.

2203
04:08:50.000 --> 04:09:05.000
You know, you might have a home health aide who goes in twice a week, but then you have a personal care provider who goes in five days a week.

2204
04:09:05.000 --> 04:09:08.000
And then we have homemaker services.

2205
04:09:08.000 --> 04:09:11.500
And this is also in class 526.

2206
04:09:11.500 --> 04:09:20.500
And this is light housekeeping, grocery shopping, changing the sheets, doing the laundry, preparing meals for the week.

2207
04:09:20.500 --> 04:09:31.000
So these are the type of services that help people remain independent and stay at home and out of nursing homes.

2208
04:09:31.000 --> 04:09:36.500
So let's talk about some of the challenges that CFI has.

2209
04:09:36.500 --> 04:09:42.000
And I think this is something that Deb Sheets addressed yesterday.

2210
04:09:42.000 --> 04:09:50.000
First of all, you have a growing caseload and that's a function of New Hampshire's demographics.

2211
04:09:50.000 --> 04:09:52.500
We are an aging state.

2212
04:09:52.500 --> 04:10:00.000
We have one of the highest levels of people over age 65 in the country.

2213
04:10:00.000 --> 04:10:11.000
And so as you can see, between 2015 and 2020, the caseload of people who relying on CFI services has really grown.

2214
04:10:11.000 --> 04:10:19.000
But then there's another real more serious challenge with increasing caseload, and that's gaps of care.

2215
04:10:19.000 --> 04:10:24.500
And when I say gaps of care, I mean undelivered services.

2216
04:10:24.500 --> 04:10:26.500
So the alliance...

2217
04:10:26.500 --> 04:10:31.500
I just want to make sure I'm understanding these percentages.

2218
04:10:31.500 --> 04:10:34.500
Are these services that are okay?

2219
04:10:34.500 --> 04:10:43.000
In this case, in skilled nursing visits, are we providing 68% of the work or only 32%?

2220
04:10:43.000 --> 04:10:50.000
We're providing 68% of the work and 32% of the authorized services are undelivered.

2221
04:10:50.000 --> 04:10:55.000
So let me just explain the process a little bit.

2222
04:10:55.000 --> 04:11:17.000
When somebody is determined to be eligible for the program, and that eligibility can take about 60 days is what Deb told you yesterday, then they are assigned an independent case manager, very much like Granite State case management that from our previous speakers.

2223
04:11:17.000 --> 04:11:30.000
That case manager, the department authorizes a range of services and says to the case manager, these are the service that the client is authorized for.

2224
04:11:30.000 --> 04:11:32.500
You go make it happen.

2225
04:11:32.500 --> 04:11:48.500
And then somebody like Carolyn Virtue will then reach out to Meals on Wheels, to a home health agency, to DME providers, to others to get them the services that they need.

2226
04:11:48.500 --> 04:12:06.000
So what I'm showing you here is that between 2017 and 2020, the department authorized a set of services and in the the case of skilled nursing, 32% of the authorized services were not delivered.

2227
04:12:06.000 --> 04:12:09.500
That's the average over the four years.

2228
04:12:09.500 --> 04:12:17.000
For home health aid, when I say short visits, it means visits under two hours.

2229
04:12:17.000 --> 04:12:22.000
45% of those visits that were authorized were not delivered.

2230
04:12:22.000 --> 04:12:32.500
For home health aid long visits, these are visits that are over two hours, 31% of the visits were not delivered.

2231
04:12:32.500 --> 04:12:43.500
In personal care, which is the largest service that is provided from home health agencies, 25% of the services were not delivered.

2232
04:12:43.500 --> 04:12:46.000
Homemaker services, 45% not delivered.

2233
04:12:46.000 --> 04:12:50.000
So let's talk about what that really means.

2234
04:12:50.000 --> 04:13:10.500
If somebody has diabetes or congestive heart failure and they need a nurse, you know, to be coming in to check on them, it means that, you know, some of their visits that they're authorized to get, they are not receiving.

2235
04:13:10.500 --> 04:13:26.000
In the case of personal care and home health aides, sometimes this is helping people get out of bed in the morning, helping them get out of bed and get dressed.

2236
04:13:26.000 --> 04:13:43.000
So if they're authorized for seven days a week to have somebody help them get undressed, and they can only receive services for five days a week, what happens on those other two days?

2237
04:13:43.000 --> 04:13:45.000
If there is...

2238
04:13:45.000 --> 04:13:56.500
come help them get undressed and they can only receive services for five days a week, what happens on those other two days?

2239
04:13:56.500 --> 04:14:03.500
If they're incontinent, it means they may not get a bath or a shower.

2240
04:14:03.500 --> 04:14:16.000
It means that their sheets that may need to be changed on a daily basis because of their incontinence don't get changed half the time.

2241
04:14:16.000 --> 04:14:37.000
And, you know, as somebody who cared for my aging parents before they died, I know how important it is for elderly people or people who have disabilities to get these services every day for the services if that's what they need.

2242
04:14:37.000 --> 04:14:39.500
Missing a day has consequences.

2243
04:14:39.500 --> 04:14:57.000
And I think that a really good example for, say, somebody who might be elderly and incontinent is that if they're not bathed regularly, if their garments not changed regularly, then they develop skin sores.

2244
04:14:57.000 --> 04:15:11.500
If they don't get out of bed every day, or if they sit in their chair all day, if they don't get up and moving, they get pressure ulcers.

2245
04:15:11.500 --> 04:15:25.500
And those pressure ulcers, if they're not seen on a regular basis by their nurse or their home health aid, can result in major infections that require hospitalizations.

2246
04:15:25.500 --> 04:15:31.500
I mean, pressure ulcers are a major risk factor for elderly people.

2247
04:15:31.500 --> 04:15:39.000
And people can be in the hospital for weeks if they get a severe infection.

2248
04:15:39.000 --> 04:15:41.500
The same thing with falls.

2249
04:15:41.500 --> 04:15:54.000
If they can't get help getting out of bed and somebody falls, it can result in injuries that end up in hospitalization and rehab stays.

2250
04:15:54.000 --> 04:15:59.000
So there are real consequences to these gaps in care.

2251
04:15:59.000 --> 04:16:07.000
And I just want the committee to understand that these gaps in care are really problematic.

2252
04:16:07.000 --> 04:16:17.000
And so the other growing challenge really is that the payments to providers are just not based on economic realities.

2253
04:16:17.000 --> 04:16:22.500
And that's part of what's contributing to the gaps in care.

2254
04:16:22.500 --> 04:16:27.000
So let's talk a little bit about provider payments.

2255
04:16:27.000 --> 04:16:43.500
So when the department pays a home care agency, they pay them based on the time that the home health aide or the personal care provider or the nurse is in the home.

2256
04:16:43.500 --> 04:17:00.000
So if the provider, if the individual is authorized for say a two-hour home health aide visit, then the payment rate that is paid to them is the rate for a two-hour visit.

2257
04:17:00.000 --> 04:17:04.500
But that visit isn't all that the agency does.

2258
04:17:04.500 --> 04:17:16.000
