2574
04:56:56.500 --> 04:57:10.000
And in particular, this is essentially the idea of closing down a prison for children, which is a movement that's been happening across the country fairly extensively.

2575
04:57:10.000 --> 04:57:30.000
And what we've seen since 1992, when the first juvenile detention alternatives initiatives started in Florida, was that children are actually harmed a bit when they go into incarceration, and they also are not effective programs to keep communities safe.

2576
04:57:30.000 --> 04:57:40.000
The most highly predictive factor of a child offending a second time is being in this system to begin with.

2577
04:57:40.000 --> 04:57:55.000
And we've also since then learned a lot about children's brains, and I'd love to give you a whole lecture about what that means when we talk about brain development.

2578
04:57:55.000 --> 04:58:03.500
And I'm happy to come back and do that at some point when you have more time.

2579
04:58:03.500 --> 04:58:18.000
But that has really sort of driven a lot of what we've known about where we put children, how we think about the things that we do with them.

2580
04:58:18.000 --> 04:58:40.500
And as we examine what are the best kinds of services for them, we've seen a shift in New Hampshire itself, building out the system of care, transforming the way we use the Sununu Center, starting with HB 517 that shifted who was admitted there.

2581
04:58:40.500 --> 04:58:44.500
And that's how we got to this place.

2582
04:58:44.500 --> 04:58:47.500
And this is a national trend.

2583
04:58:47.500 --> 04:58:55.500
We're seeing significantly that fewer and fewer children are being arrested and brought into juvenile systems.

2584
04:58:55.500 --> 04:58:58.500
This is a really good indicator.

2585
04:58:58.500 --> 04:59:07.500
Right now, as I mentioned to you today, there are 13 children at the Sununi Youth Services Center.

2586
04:59:07.500 --> 04:59:13.500
There's actually about a little over 1,700 children who are adjudicated delinquent.

2587
04:59:13.500 --> 04:59:17.500
Most of them are served in the community.

2588
04:59:17.500 --> 04:59:21.500
It's a very small population that are incarcerated.

2589
04:59:21.500 --> 04:59:36.000
And I include the number of children who are in residential placements because in some ways, you know, courts order children to these placements as an alternative to incarceration.

2590
04:59:36.000 --> 04:59:44.500
And there are some of the similar concerns about kids who are in those environments as well.

2591
04:59:44.500 --> 04:59:56.000
Right now, there are 39 children who are delinquent, adjudicated delinquent in the state, and 13 who have been sent out of state.

2592
04:59:56.000 --> 05:00:01.500
Many of the kids who are out of state are girls.

2593
05:00:01.500 --> 05:00:10.500
Of the 11 children that are at the Sununu Center today, two are detained and nine are committed.

2594
05:00:10.500 --> 05:00:15.500
We use the same facility for both detention and commitment.

2595
05:00:15.500 --> 05:00:23.500
At least two of the children are awaiting placement options for foster care or residential programming.

2596
05:00:23.500 --> 05:00:25.500
There are probably more.

2597
05:00:25.500 --> 05:00:34.500
It's our opinion that most of the children who are there could be treated safely in the community.

2598
05:00:34.500 --> 05:00:48.000
There are eight children there at police who have combined history with 82 abuse and neglect referrals ranging from seven for one child to 31 for another.

2599
05:00:48.000 --> 05:00:52.500
So these are the crossover children that we see.

2600
05:00:52.500 --> 05:01:20.000
They're children who have lived through abuse and neglect and the behavior that manifests because of their treatment and their adverse childhood experiences ends up being involved with law enforcement and adjudicated and sometimes just brought over to the juvenile system in order to get them the idea that they're getting some sort of help.

2601
05:01:20.000 --> 05:01:26.500
There are three children also who've had child in need of services cases.

2602
05:01:26.500 --> 05:01:34.000
Those are children who have behavioral issues that they can't get services any other way.

2603
05:01:34.000 --> 05:01:39.500
There are four that have been in multiple residential programs already.

2604
05:01:39.500 --> 05:01:45.000
And there are six who are there because of parole violations.

2605
05:01:45.000 --> 05:01:50.500
So that is the recidivism that you see people coming back.

2606
05:01:50.500 --> 05:02:09.000
So one of the quick things I'll just say, since I can't lecture you entirely on brain development, is some of the things that we need to think about when we think about where we're putting children.

2607
05:02:09.000 --> 05:02:24.500
We all have become in New Hampshire really sort of expert about being responsive to trauma and understanding what happens to children when they have been traumatized or adverse childhood experiences.

2608
05:02:24.500 --> 05:02:39.500
But the other side of that that we need to be thinking about is how to heal children, what will make them healthy and get their development back on track.

2609
05:02:39.500 --> 05:02:53.000
So there are four sort of pillars of hope that Robert Zaghi and his colleagues use to describe the important things that will help children be successful.

2610
05:02:53.000 --> 05:03:04.500
One is that consistent caring adult, an adult who is committed to a child and the child feels they have that strong relationship.

2611
05:03:04.500 --> 05:03:15.500
The next is to live, play, and learn in a safe, stable environment and not to be in fear all the time.

2612
05:03:15.500 --> 05:03:22.000
And then the third is to feel that you belong to a community.

2613
05:03:22.000 --> 05:03:32.000
So it's really important when you move kids away from a community, they lose that and they don't feel valued.

2614
05:03:32.000 --> 05:03:36.000
You want to have that sense of belonging.

2615
05:03:36.000 --> 05:03:49.000
And then finally, to be given the skills to be able to manage their emotions in a healthy way, which is how they'll manage their behaviors.

2616
05:03:49.000 --> 05:04:05.000
So it's been very difficult to talk with folks about considering closing down a youth prison and right now in the United States because New Hampshire is so far ahead of everyone.

2617
05:04:05.000 --> 05:04:14.000
I mean, there really are a lot of eyes on this state for the progress that we've made.

2618
05:04:14.000 --> 05:04:19.500
And I know for many people, it doesn't feel that way.

2619
05:04:19.500 --> 05:04:44.000
But the idea of trying to resolve an issue of 11 kids who are in a facility is almost sort of adorable to many of the states around us who are dealing with hundreds of kids, and they consider themselves fully transformed and doing different ways of juvenile justice.

2620
05:04:44.000 --> 05:04:55.000
But when you have conversations with them, they'll tell you before you close the facility, you have to have all these things.

2621
05:04:55.000 --> 05:05:07.500
And all of the things they mentioned are things that we either have, or we're in the process, thanks to Senate Bill 14 from 2019.

2622
05:05:07.500 --> 05:05:21.000
The mobile crisis response that not just helps kids at home, but actually goes to schools and where a lot of offenses come from the school environment.

2623
05:05:21.000 --> 05:05:25.500
So instead of police responding, you have clinicians responding.

2624
05:05:25.500 --> 05:05:37.500
These expanded wraparound care coordinating services that work with families and children to help them manage issues at home so that minimizes behavioral problems.

2625
05:05:37.500 --> 05:05:50.500
We have an RFP out right now for multisystemic therapy, which is the most evidence-based intensive program for children to keep them out of incarcerated situations.

2626
05:05:50.500 --> 05:06:02.500
MST for about the average length of stay is three to four months for about, I think it's up to $15,000 roundabout per child.

2627
05:06:02.500 --> 05:06:14.500
And there are evidences that not only will that child not re-offend, but that child's siblings won't offend and the child's parents won't offend.

2628
05:06:14.500 --> 05:06:17.000
It's a really exceptional program.

2629
05:06:17.000 --> 05:06:21.500
We're very excited that it's coming to New Hampshire.

2630
05:06:21.500 --> 05:06:47.500
And the care management entities and the comprehensive assessment treatment, these are essentially they're independent bodies who are going to be looking at kids, assessing their needs and matching them to services so that they don't end up just placed randomly in residential care that's not really designed to meet their needs.

2631
05:06:47.500 --> 05:06:54.500
And they're going to be watching them to make sure that they're making progress.

2632
05:06:54.500 --> 05:07:11.500
So it's when children are placed someplace for care and it's not adequate for them that they start sliding and they end up in an assaultive situation and end up at the Sununu Center.

2633
05:07:11.500 --> 05:07:36.500
And there's also an RFP out for actual procured residential services that will be under contract for the first time so that we can hold providers accountable to provide services that are effective and that meet children's needs and that children move on rapidly to get back to their community.

2634
05:07:36.500 --> 05:07:42.000
So they have that sense of belonging and maintaining those relationships.

2635
05:07:42.000 --> 05:07:46.000
And there's also a whole probation transformation happening.

2636
05:07:46.000 --> 05:08:05.000
And there's a bill, Senate Bill 94, I think, that would that would have the law enforcement when they encounter a child who's broken the law, can refer them to the department for an assessment of their needs.

2637
05:08:05.000 --> 05:08:18.500
And if we discover that their needs would, if they were met, would also mitigate the risk to the community, then they never get petitions for adjudication.

2638
05:08:18.500 --> 05:08:24.500
They just go right to whatever service is going to help them.

2639
05:08:24.500 --> 05:08:27.000
So I'm mentioning these things.

2640
05:08:27.000 --> 05:08:49.000
I know you've heard a lot about some of them in the conversations with the department the last couple of weeks, but I'm mentioning these in the context of, this is gonna drive a more diminishing rate of children coming into the Sununu Center.

2641
05:08:49.000 --> 05:08:53.500
It's almost gonna empty out just sort of organically.

2642
05:08:53.500 --> 05:09:08.500
But we know that people believe that we still need some alternative when we have to, when we have a child that we need to keep safe from the community.

2643
05:09:08.500 --> 05:09:23.000
And so we propose the two models that we spent the last week really talking to experts around the country to see, you know, what are the best models.

2644
05:09:23.000 --> 05:09:34.000
